  "prompt": "In how many ways can we distribute 10 identical looking pencils to 4 students so that each student gets at least one pencil?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) This is a classic stars and bars problem with a minimum constraint.\n\n2) To ensure each student gets at least one pencil, we first give one pencil to each student.\n\n3) Now we have 6 pencils (10 - 4 = 6) to distribute freely among the 4 students.\n\n4) This is equivalent to finding the number of ways to put 6 identical pencils into 4 distinct groups, which is a standard stars and bars problem.\n\n5) The stars and bars formula for distributing n identical objects into k distinct groups is:\n   \u2022 Number of ways = (n + k - 1)! / (n! * (k - 1)!)\n\n6) Here, n = 6 (remaining pencils) and k = 4 (number of students)\n\n7) Plugging in the numbers:\n   \u2022 Ways = (6 + 4 - 1)! / (6! * (4 - 1)!)\n   \u2022 Ways = 9! / (6! * 3!)\n\n8) Let's calculate:\n   \u2022 9! = 362,880\n   \u2022 6! = 720\n   \u2022 3! = 6\n   \u2022 9! / (6! * 3!) = 362,880 / (720 * 6)\n   \u2022 9! / (6! * 3!) = 362,880 / 4,320\n   \u2022 9! / (6! * 3!) = 84\n\nTherefore, there are 84 ways to distribute 10 pencils to 4 students with each student getting at least one pencil.",
